%I A392373 #57 May 26 2026 21:07:13
%S A392373 6,15,35,55,77,91,119,143,187,209,221,247,299,323,377,391,437,493,527,
%T A392373 551,589,667,703,713,779,851,899,943,989,1073,1081,1147,1189,1247,
%U A392373 1271,1333,1363,1457,1517,1537,1591,1643,1739,1763,1829,1891,1927,1961,2021,2173,2183
%N A392373 Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct squarefree semiprimes (A006881) with the property that, for all k >= 1, the k-th prime divides exactly k terms.
%C A392373 The terms are created by choosing the smallest prime p(k) that is not yet a factor in k terms, and then adding a new terms p(k)*p(k+1), p(k)*p(k+2), ... . New terms are added until k such terms exist, where one must also consider the number of previous terms that already contain p(k) as a factor. The resulting list is then sorted.
%H A392373 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A392373/b392373_2.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A392373 a(1) = 6 = 2*3. This satisfies p(1) = 2 being a factor of one term.
%e A392373 a(2) = 15 = 3*5. Along with a(1) = 6 this satisfies p(2) = 3 being a factor of two terms.
%e A392373 a(3) = 35, a(4) = 55. Along with a(2) = 15 these satisfy p(3) = 5 being a factor of three terms.
%Y A392373 Cf. A006881, A395360, A395970, A395795.
%K A392373 nonn,changed
